::BLUF Technique::What does BLUF stand for and why is it used in business email?{
="Bottom Line Up Front" - technique of stating main point first, developed by U.S. military to maximize communication effectiveness and reduce follow-up questions #BLUF stands for "Bottom Line Up Front" and was developed by the U.S. military to ensure critical information is communicated immediately. Sehgal's HBR article (2016) explains that military professionals lead emails with this technique to answer the five W's (who, what, where, when, why) in the opening, maximizing mission success through precise communication. The technique reduces follow-up questions by 30-40% according to military research and ensures key message is received even if email is only partially read.
~"Brief, Logical, Unified, Focused" - framework for organizing email paragraphs sequentially #Acronym is incorrect - BLUF is not about "Brief, Logical, Unified, Focused" sequencing
~"Business Language Usage Format" - professional writing standard for formal correspondence #Not "Business Language Usage Format" - this is fabricated terminology
~"Baseline Understanding For Letters" - method for establishing common ground with recipients #Not "Baseline Understanding For Letters" - misses the core concept of stating conclusion first
