::Subject Line Keywords::According to Sehgal's military email framework, which keyword should you use in a subject line when you need the recipient to make a decision between options?{
~ACTION #ACTION is for emails requiring a response/action, but not specifically for decision-making between options
~REQUEST #REQUEST is for seeking approval or permission, which is different from asking recipient to decide between alternatives
=DECISION #According to Sehgal's military email framework, "DECISION" is the keyword used when the email requires recipient to make a judgment or choose between options. Other keywords include ACTION (requires response), INFO (FYI only), REQUEST (seeks approval), SIGN (needs signature), and COORD (coordination needed). These keywords force the sender to clarify their intent before writing.
~COORD #COORD is for coordination activities, not decision-making
}

::Active vs. Passive Voice::Which sentence uses ACTIVE voice and is therefore clearer and more effective for business email?{
~"The budget proposal was submitted by the finance team last Friday." #"was submitted by" is passive voice construction - action before actor
~"It has been determined that the meeting will be postponed until next month." #"It has been determined" is passive and vague - no agent identified
="The finance team submitted the budget proposal last Friday." #"The finance team submitted the budget proposal last Friday" uses active voice with clear subject (finance team) performing action (submitted). This structure is clearer, more direct, and 10% faster to read according to Birchard's neuroscience research. Active voice also creates accountability by identifying who did what.
~"A decision was reached regarding the timeline for the project." #"A decision was reached" is passive - doesn't identify who decided
}

::Processing Fluency::According to Birchard's neuroscience research, what effect does passive voice have on reading comprehension?{
~Increases comprehension accuracy by 10% due to more formal structure #Opposite of research finding - passive reduces, not increases comprehension
=Reduces comprehension accuracy by 10% and slows reading speed #Birchard's neuroscience research (2021) found that passive voice reduces comprehension accuracy by 10% and slows reading speed. This is because brain must work harder to identify the agent of action and reconstruct meaning. "Processing fluency" refers to how easily brain understands and remembers information - simpler structures create better fluency.
~Has no significant effect on comprehension but sounds more professional #Research shows passive DOES significantly affect comprehension (10% reduction)
~Improves memory retention by 15% through complex sentence structure #Passive doesn't improve memory - active voice is better remembered
}

::Tone Adaptation::You need to tell your professor you cannot attend their office hours tomorrow. Which greeting and tone level is most appropriate?{
~"Hey Prof! Quick heads up..." (Casual) #"Hey Prof!" is far too casual for professor communication - could damage professional relationship
~"Hi Dr. Nguyen, Unfortunately I have a conflict..." (Professional) #"Hi Dr. Nguyen, Unfortunately..." is professional but not formal enough for this context (missing scheduled appointment with authority figure)
="Dear Dr. Nguyen, I regret to inform you..." (Formal) #Communication with a professor about missing office hours requires formal tone, especially if this is not an established relationship. "Dear Dr. Nguyen, I regret to inform you..." shows appropriate respect for authority figure, uses formal greeting (Dear + title + name), and formal language ("regret to inform"). This tone level matches high-stakes context and hierarchical relationship.
~"What's up? Just FYI..." (Very casual) #"What's up? Just FYI..." is completely inappropriate - would be seen as disrespectful
}

::Specificity in Business Writing::According to neuroscience research, why are concrete words (like "pelican") more effective than abstract words (like "bird")?{
~Concrete words are shorter and therefore faster to type #Length has nothing to do with why concrete words are effective - focus is neural activation
=Concrete words activate more neurons in visual and motor brain regions, causing brain to process meaning more robustly #Birchard's neuroscience research found that concrete words like "pelican" activate more neurons in visual and motor brain regions than abstract words like "bird," causing "the brain to process meaning more robustly." When brain creates specific mental image (pelican \= large water bird with pouch), it engages multiple neural pathways, leading to deeper processing and better memory retention. This is why specific details (dates, numbers, names) more memorable than vague language.
~Concrete words are more formal and therefore more professional #Formality not the reason - concrete words work because of brain processing, not professional tone
~Concrete words reduce email length by 25% #Research doesn't claim 25% length reduction - benefit is comprehension and memory
}

