::Call-to-Action::An effective call-to-action (CTA) in a business email should include\:{
~Only a polite request with no deadline to avoid seeming demanding #No deadline reduces urgency and accountability - request likely to be forgotten or deprioritized
~Multiple options so recipient can choose their preferred action #Multiple options create decision paralysis - make it easy by recommending specific action
=Specific action requested and clear deadline for completion #An effective CTA specifies WHAT action you need and WHEN (deadline) to make it easy for recipient to respond and create accountability. Vague CTAs like "let me know" or "when you have time" reduce response rates because recipient must figure out what to do and when. Specific CTAs ("Please send completed spreadsheet by Friday, March 15 at 5pm") increase response rates by 20-30% according to email effectiveness research.
~General statement like "Let me know if you have questions" #"Let me know if you have questions" is passive, not actionable - doesn't tell recipient what to DO
}
